Given a cyclic proof with a cycle *, with cycle map f \rightsquigarrow  \theta :  


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma '' \vdash  \psi ''$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\vdots $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ' \vdash  \psi '$}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
      \BinaryInfC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}


  we define its unrolling as the cyclic proof:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {*\ $f(\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ') \vdash  f(\psi ')$}
      \AxiomC {$f(\Sigma )$}
      \BinaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma '' \vdash  \psi ''$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\vdots $}
      \UnaryInfC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ' \vdash  \psi '$}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
      \BinaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}

Aside from what we discussed last week, there is still an issue with weakening along cycles, specifically nested ones. Consider the following situation:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ' \vdash  \psi '$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\vdots $}
      \UnaryInfC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
      \LeftLabel {\small  (wk$_y$)}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma , y : \chi  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}


  Even if the weakening is "good" with respect to the * cycle, it may be that there is another cycle that overlaps * which the weakening is "bad" with respect to. This would mean that we cannot just look at the companion above a weakening rule to decide whether we can weaken along the entire proof above that companion. I think that part of this problem stems from unfoldings being "big-step" in some sense, so I proposed that we consider "unrollings" of cyclic proofs instead - a "small-step" kind of cycle unfolding.

Given a cyclic proof with a cycle *, with cycle map f \rightsquigarrow  \theta :  


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma '' \vdash  \psi ''$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\vdots $}
      \UnaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ' \vdash  \psi '$}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
      \BinaryInfC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}


  we define its unrolling as the cyclic proof:


    \usepackage {bussproofs, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs, amsmath}
    \newenvironment {bprooftree}
      {\leavevmode \hbox \bgroup }
      {\DisplayProof \egroup }

    \begin {bprooftree}
      \AxiomC {*\ $f(\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ') \vdash  f(\psi ')$}
      \AxiomC {$f(\Sigma )$}
      \BinaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma '' \vdash  \psi ''$}
      \UnaryInfC {$\vdots $}
      \UnaryInfC {*\ $\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma ' \vdash  \psi '$}
      \AxiomC {$\Sigma $}
      \BinaryInfC {$\mathcal {H} ; \Gamma  \vdash  \psi $}
    \end {bprooftree}
